<glossary>
<definition id="fs-id1166424847478">
<term>absolute value</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1166424809754">The absolute value of a number is its distance from 0 on the number line. The absolute value of a number <m:math><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:math> is written as <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>|</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>|</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1166424772590">
<term>integers</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1166424772595">The whole numbers and their opposites are called the integers: ...−3, −2, −1, 0, 1, 2, 3...</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-id1166422694257">
<term>opposite</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1166422694262">The opposite of a number is the number that is the same distance from zero on the number line but on the opposite side of zero: <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>−</m:mtext><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> means the opposite of the number. The notation <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>−</m:mtext><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> is read “the opposite of <m:math><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:math>.”</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
